Activist and educator Mary McLeod Bethune was instrumental in advancing education at historically Black colleges and universities throughout the country.
Statue of Mary Mcleod Bethune will become the first of a Black woman in the U.S. Capitol thanks to the efforts of CBC Member @RepValDemings.
By the way, Bethune’s statue will replace a statue of former confederate general Edmund Kirby Smith.
She launched the National Council of Negro Women as an avenue to create opportunities for Black women and their families.
“Mary McLeod Bethune was the most powerful woman I can remember as a child,” she said in a statement, according to the news outlet.